history.content:
1.) email Rao

2.) ay least as much as 170 probably
3.) yes
-------------------
1) Talk to Rao
2) Probably a lot less than 170. The content might be delivered faster (which will be tough if it is your first time in a grad course) but there will probably be less/no homework.
3) There are few 5 unit CS classes, but 3 units is standard for a lot of grad classes.

Also don't tunnel vision on 270! There are other interesting grad courses offered every semester: for example, are you also considering at probabilistically checkable and interactive proofs?
-------------------
CS 172 is also a good choice~

children.subject: You can take 152 (it's 5 units). I think there's also a couple of EECS classes that are 5 units, but unless you know a lot of physics and electromechanics probably they won't be an option :(
I don't think that courses taken on a P/NP basis can be applied to the upper division unit requirement.
You can also take another 4 unit + CS 195 (Social Implications of Computing) to make 5 units

@last anon I am very serious about considering multiple options: there are a few ways to get involved in Theory and a few undergrads and I have organized a new club: Undergraduate Group for Theoretical Computing: https://ugtcs.github.io/. If anyone here is interested in theory, you should come to some meetings!
